{"title_page": "Sukagawa Station", "text_new": "{{short description|Railway station in Sukagawa, Fukushima Prefecture, Japan}}\n{{refimprove|date=May 2018}}\n{{Infobox station\n| name        = Sukagawa Station\n| native_name = \u9808\u8cc0\u5ddd\u99c5\n| native_name_lang = ja\n| type        = \n| image       = Sukagawa station 20120906.jpg\n| alt         = \n| caption     = Sukagawa Station in September 2012\n| other_name  = \n| address     = 63-1 Nakayama, Sukagawa-shi, Fukushima-ken 962-0004\n| country     = Japan\n| coordinates = {{Coord|37.3002|N|140.3724|E|type:railwaystation_region:JP|display=title, inline}}\n| operator    = [[File:JR logo (east).svg|20px]] [[JR East]]\n| line        = {{Colorbull|MediumSeaGreen}} [[T\u014dhoku Main Line]]\n| distance    = 215.1 km from {{STN|Tokyo}}\n| platforms   = 2 side platforms\n| tracks      =  \n| connections = Bus stop\n| structure   = \n| code        = \n| status      = Staffed (''[[Midori no Madoguchi]]'')\n| website     = {{Official website|1=http://www.jreast.co.jp/estation/station/info.aspx?StationCd=895}}\n| opened      = July 16, 1887\n| closed      = \n| former      =  \n| passengers  = 2307 daily\n| pass_year   = FY2016\n| map_type    = Japan Fukushima Prefecture#Japan   \n| map_dot_label       = Sukagawa Station\n}}\n \n{{nihongo|'''Sukagawa Station'''|\u9808\u8cc0\u5ddd\u99c5|Sukagawa-eki}} is a [[railway station]] in the city of [[Sukagawa, Fukushima|Sukagawa]], [[Fukushima Prefecture]], Japan, operated by [[East Japan Railway Company]] (JR East).\n\n==Overview==\n*This station is a representative station of Sukagawa City, and is the closest station to the city center, Midorigaoka Park, Sukagawa Botan Garden and Yoshimine Fuji Garden.\n\n==Lines==\nSukagawa Station is served by the [[T\u014dhoku Main Line]], and is located 215.1 kilometers from the official starting point of the line at [[Tokyo Station]].\n\n==Station layout==\nThe station has two opposed [[side platform]]s. The station has a ''[[Midori no Madoguchi]]'' staffed ticket office.\n\n===Platforms===\n{{ja-rail-line|pfn=1|first=2|name= T\u014dhoku Main Line |linecol=MediumSeaGreen|dir= for {{STN|Shin-Shirakawa}} and {{STN|Kuroiso}}}} \n{{ja-rail-line|pfn=2|first=3|nidx= T\u014dhoku Main Line |linecol=MediumSeaGreen|dir= for {{STN|K\u014driyama|Fukushima}} and {{STN|Fukushima|Fukushima}}}}\n==Operation from at this station==\n*Upbound (for [[Yabuki Station|Yabuki]], [[Shirakawa Station|Shirakawa]] & [[Shin-Shirakawa Station|Shin-Shirakawa]])\n**During the day, one ordinary train (for Shin-Shirakawa) stops approximately every hour. Some trains also have Yabuki and Shirakawa lines. If you use the [[Kuroiso Station|Kuroiso]] area from this station, you need to transfer at Shin-Shirakawa.\n*Downhill (for [[K\u014driyama Station (Fukushima) |K\u014driyama]], [[Motomiya Station|Motomiya]] & [[Fukushima Station (Fukushima)|Fukushima]])\n**During the day, as in the case of climbing, one ordinary train (bound for Koriyama) stops approximately every hour. Some trains are also set up for Fukushima north of Koriyama and for [[Sendai Station (Miyagi)|Sendai]].\n\n==Adjacent stations==\n{{J-railservice start}}\n{{J-route|route=T\u014dhoku Main Line|col=MediumSeaGreen|f=w}}\n{{J-rserv|service=-|previous={{STN|Kagamiishi}}|next={{STN|Asaka-Nagamori}}}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n==History==\nSukagawa Station opened on July 16, 1887. The station was absorbed into the JR East network upon the privatization of the [[Japanese National Railways]] (JNR) on April 1, 1987.\n\n==Passenger statistics==\nIn fiscal 2018, the station was used by an average of 2,294 passengers daily (boarding passengers only). <ref name=\"jreast2018stats\">{{cite web |url=http://www.jreast.co.jp/passenger/2018_04.html|script-title=ja: \u5404\u99c5\u306e\u4e57\u8eca\u4eba\u54e1 (2018\u5e74\u5ea6)|trans-title=Station passenger figures (Fiscal 2018)|year= 2019|publisher= East Japan Railway Company|location= Japan|language= Japanese|archiveurl= |archivedate= |accessdate= 2 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Surrounding area==\n*Sukagawa City Hall\n*{{jct|country=JPN|Route|4}}\n*{{jct|country=JPN|Route|118}}\n*Sukagawa Post Office\n*[[Abukuma River]]\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of railway stations in Japan]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* {{Official website|1=http://www.jreast.co.jp/estation/station/info.aspx?StationCd=895}} {{in lang|ja}}\n\n{{Tohoku Main Line}}\n\n[[Category:Railway stations in Fukushima Prefecture]]\n[[Category:T\u014dhoku Main Line]]\n[[Category:Railway stations opened in 1887]]\n[[Category:Stations of East Japan Railway Company]]\n[[Category:1887 establishments in Japan]]\n[[Category:Sukagawa, Fukushima]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Railway station in Sukagawa, Fukushima Prefecture, Japan}}\n{{refimprove|date=May 2018}}\n{{Infobox station\n| name        = Sukagawa Station\n| native_name = \u9808\u8cc0\u5ddd\u99c5\n| native_name_lang = ja\n| type        = \n| image       = Sukagawa station 20120906.jpg\n| alt         = \n| caption     = Sukagawa Station in September 2012\n| other_name  = \n| address     = 63-1 Nakayama, Sukagawa-shi, Fukushima-ken 962-0004\n| country     = Japan\n| coordinates = {{Coord|37.3002|N|140.3724|E|type:railwaystation_region:JP|display=title, inline}}\n| operator    = [[File:JR logo (east).svg|20px]] [[JR East]]\n| line        = {{Colorbull|MediumSeaGreen}} [[T\u014dhoku Main Line]]\n| distance    = 215.1 km from {{STN|Tokyo}}\n| platforms   = 2 side platforms\n| tracks      =  \n| connections = Bus stop\n| structure   = \n| code        = \n| status      = Staffed (''[[Midori no Madoguchi]]'')\n| website     = {{Official website|1=http://www.jreast.co.jp/estation/station/info.aspx?StationCd=895}}\n| opened      = July 16, 1887\n| closed      = \n| former      =  \n| passengers  = 2307 daily\n| pass_year   = FY2016\n| map_type    = Japan\n}}\n \n{{nihongo|'''Sukagawa Station'''|\u9808\u8cc0\u5ddd\u99c5|Sukagawa-eki}} is a railway station on the [[T\u014dhoku Main Line]] in the city of [[Sukagawa, Fukushima|Sukagawa]], [[Fukushima Prefecture]], Japan, operated by [[East Japan Railway Company]] (JR East).\n\n==Overview==\n*This station is a representative station of Sukagawa City, and is the closest station to the city center, Midorigaoka Park, Sukagawa Botan Garden and Yoshimine Fuji Garden.\n\n==Lines==\nSukagawa Station is served by the [[T\u014dhoku Main Line]], and is located 215.1 kilometers from the official starting point of the line at [[Tokyo Station]].\n\n==Station layout==\nSukagawa Station has two opposed [[side platform]]s. The station has a ''[[Midori no Madoguchi]]'' staffed ticket office.\n\n===Platforms===\n{{ja-rail-line|pfn=1|first=2|name= T\u014dhoku Main Line |linecol=MediumSeaGreen|dir= for {{STN|Shin-Shirakawa}} and {{STN|Kuroiso}}}} \n{{ja-rail-line|pfn=2|first=3|nidx= T\u014dhoku Main Line |linecol=MediumSeaGreen|dir= for {{STN|K\u014driyama|Fukushima}} and {{STN|Fukushima|Fukushima}}}}\n==Operation form at this station==\n*Upbound (for [[Yabuki Station|Yabuki]], [[Shirakawa Station|Shirakawa]] & [[Shin-Shirakawa Station|Shin-Shirakawa]])\n**During the day, one ordinary train (for Shin-Shirakawa) stops approximately every hour. Some trains also have Yabuki and Shirakawa lines. If you use the [[Kuroiso Station|Kuroiso]] area from this station, you need to transfer at Shin-Shirakawa.\n*Downhill (for [[K\u014driyama Station (Fukushima) |K\u014driyama]], [[Motomiya Station|Motomiya]] & [[Fukushima Station (Fukushima)|Fukushima]])\n**During the day, as in the case of climbing, one ordinary train (bound for Koriyama) stops approximately every hour. Some trains are also set up for Fukushima north of Koriyama and for [[Sendai Station (Miyagi)|Sendai]].\n\n==Adjacent stations==\n{{J-railservice start}}\n{{J-route|route=T\u014dhoku Main Line|col=MediumSeaGreen|f=w}}\n{{J-rserv|service=-|previous={{STN|Kagamiishi}}|next={{STN|Asaka-Nagamori}}}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n==History==\nSukagawa Station opened on July 16, 1887. The station was absorbed into the JR East network upon the privatization of the [[Japanese National Railways]] (JNR) on April 1, 1987.\n\n==Passenger statistics==\nIn fiscal 2016, the station was used by an average of 2,307 passengers daily (boarding passengers only). <ref name=\"jreast2016stats\">{{cite web |url=http://www.jreast.co.jp/passenger/2016_04.html|script-title=ja: \u5404\u99c5\u306e\u4e57\u8eca\u4eba\u54e1 (2016\u5e74\u5ea6)|trans-title=Station passenger figures (Fiscal 2016)|year= 2017|publisher= East Japan Railway Company|location= Japan|language= Japanese|archiveurl= |archivedate= |accessdate= 2 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Surrounding area==\n*Sukagawa City Hall\n*{{jct|country=JPN|Route|4}}\n*{{jct|country=JPN|Route|118}}\n*Sukagawa Post Office\n*[[Abukuma River]]\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of railway stations in Japan]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* {{Official website|1=http://www.jreast.co.jp/estation/station/info.aspx?StationCd=895}} {{in lang|ja}}\n\n{{Tohoku Main Line}}\n\n[[Category:Railway stations in Fukushima Prefecture]]\n[[Category:T\u014dhoku Main Line]]\n[[Category:Railway stations opened in 1887]]\n[[Category:Stations of East Japan Railway Company]]\n[[Category:1887 establishments in Japan]]\n[[Category:Sukagawa, Fukushima]]\n", "name_user": "MChew", "label": "safe", "comment": "replace map", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sukagawa_Station"}
{"title_page": "Loya jirga", "text_new": "{{short description|Pashtun legal assembly convened for major national issues}}\n[[File:Hamid Karzai became winner at the 2002 Loya Jirga.jpg|thumb|300px|right|[[Hamid Karzai]] appointed as President of the [[List of Afghan Transitional Administration personnel|Afghan Transitional Administration]] at the [[2002 Loya Jirga|13 July 2002]] ''loya jirga'' held in [[Kabul]], [[Afghanistan]].]]\n\nA '''''loya jirga''''' ({{lang-ps|\u0644\u0648\u064a\u0647 \u062c\u0631\u06ab\u0647}}, \"grand assembly\") is a special type of ''[[jirga]]'', or legal assembly, in [[Pashtunwali]], the traditional code of laws of the [[Pashtun people]]. It is mainly organized for choosing a new [[head of state]] in case of sudden death, adopting a new constitution, or to settle national or regional issue such as war.<ref name=\"news.bbc.co.uk\">{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/1782079.stm | work=BBC News | title=Q&A: What is a loya jirga? | date=July 1, 2002 | accessdate=May 11, 2010}}</ref> It predates modern-day written or fixed laws and is mostly favored by the [[Pashtun people]] but to a lesser extent by other nearby groups that have been influenced by Pashtuns (historically known as [[Afghan (ethnonym)|Afghans]]).\n\nIn [[Afghanistan]], ''loya jirgas'' have been reportedly organized since at least the early 18th century when the [[Hotaki dynasty|Hotaki]] and [[Durrani dynasty|Durrani]] dynasties rose to power.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/09/11/opinion/11krakauer.html?scp=8&sq=jon%20krakauer&st=cse |title=To Save Afghanistan, Look to Its Past |author=Jon Krakauer |newspaper=New York Times |date=September 11, 2009 |accessdate=2014-10-29}}</ref>\n\n==History and terminology ==\n\nThere is a myth in the sense that the ancient [[Aryan]] tribes, who are hypothesized to have spoken [[Proto-Indo-Iranian language|Proto-Indo-Iranian]], came down in intermittent waves from [[Central Asia]] and Afghanistan. They practiced a sort of ''jirga'' system with two types of councils \u2013 ''{{transl|pus|simite}}'' and ''{{transl|pus|sabh\u0101}}''. The ''{{transl|pus|simite}}'' (summit) comprised elders and tribal chiefs. The king also joined sessions of the ''{{transl|pus|simite}}''. ''Sabh\u0101'' was a sort of rural council. In India it is referred to as ''Samiti'' and ''Sabha''.\n\nIt was used over time for the selection of rulers and headmen and the airing of matters of principle. From the time of the great Kushan ruler [[Kanishka]] to the 1970s, there were sixteen [[nation]]al ''loya jirgas'' and hundreds of smaller ones. The institution, which is centuries old, is a similar idea to the Islamic ''[[shura]]'' (consultative assembly).<ref name=\"news.bbc.co.uk\"/>\n\nIn the [[Demographics of Afghanistan|Afghan society]], the ''loya jirga'' is still maintained and favored, mostly by tribal leaders to solve internal or external disputes with other tribes. In some cases it functions like a [[town hall meeting]].\n\nWhen the Afghans took power they tried to legitimize their hold with such a ''jirga''. While in the beginning only Pashtuns were allowed to participate in the ''jirgas'', later other ethnic groups like [[Tajik people|Tajiks]] and [[Hazara people|Hazaras]] were allowed to participate as well, however they were little more than observers. The member of the ''jirgas'' were mostly members of the Royal Family, religious leaders and tribal leaders of the Afghans. King [[Amanullah Khan]] institutionalized the ''jirga''. From Amanullah until the reign of [[Mohammed Zahir Shah]] (1933\u20131973) and [[Mohammed Daoud Khan]] (1973\u20131978) the ''jirga'' was recognized as a common meeting of regional Pashtun leaders.\n\nThe meetings do not have scheduled occurrences, but rather are called for when issues or disputes arise. There is no time limit for a ''loya jirga'' to conclude, and the meetings often take time because decisions can only be made as a group and arguments can drag out for days. Various issues can be addressed such as major disaster, foreign policy, declaration of war, the legitimacy of leaders, and the introduction of new ideas and laws.\n\n==Afghanistan==\nSome of the historical ''loya jirgas'' in the [[history of Afghanistan]] are:\n*'''1707\u20131709''' \u2013 ''Loya jirga'' was gathered by [[Mir Wais Hotak]] at [[Kandahar]] in 1707, but according to [[Ghulam Mohammad Ghobar]] it was gathered in Manja in 1709.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://wolas.beepworld.de/mirwaisneeka.htm |title=Mirwais Neeka |publisher=Wolas.beepworld.de |date= |accessdate=2013-04-15}}</ref>\n*'''October 1747''' \u2013 A ''jirga'' at [[Kandahar]] was attended by Afghan representatives who appointed [[Ahmad Shah Durrani]] as their new leader.\n*'''September 1928''' \u2013 A ''jirga'' at [[Paghman]], called by [[King Amanullah]], the third loya jirga of his reign (1919\u20131929) to discuss reforms.\n*'''September 1930''' \u2013 A ''jirga'' of 286 called by [[Mohammed Nadir Shah]] to confirm his accession to the throne.\n*'''1941''' \u2013 Called by [[Mohammed Zahir Shah]] to approve neutrality in [[World War II]].\n*'''1947''' \u2013 Held by Pashtuns in the [[FATA|Tribal Agencies]] to choose between joining [[India]] or [[Pakistan]].\n*'''July 26, 1949''' \u2013 [[Afghanistan-Pakistan relations]] rapidly deteriorated over a dispute, officially declared that it did not recognize the 1893 [[Durand Line]] border any longer between the two countries.<ref>Agha Amin, [http://www.chowk.com/ilogs/65724/47736 \"Resolving the Afghan-Pakistan Border Question\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081012045458/http://www.chowk.com/ilogs/65724/47736 |date=October 12, 2008}}, ''Journal of Afghanistan Studies'', Kabul, (accessed December 12, 2009).</ref>\n*'''September 1964''' \u2013 A meeting of 452 called by [[Mohammed Zahir Shah]] to approve a new constitution.\n*'''July 1974''' \u2013 A meeting with Pakistan over the Durand Line.\n*'''[[1977 Afghan Constitutional Assembly election|January 1977]]''' \u2013 Approved the new constitution of [[Mohammed Daoud Khan]] establishing one-party rule in the [[Daouds Republic of Afghanistan|Republic of Afghanistan]].\n*'''April 1985''' \u2013 To ratify the new constitution of the [[Democratic Republic of Afghanistan]].\n*'''September 2001''' \u2013 Four different loya jirga movements anticipating the end of [[Taliban]] rule. Little communication took place between each of them.\n**The first was based in [[Rome]] around [[Mohammed Zahir Shah]], and it reflected the interests of moderate Pashtuns from Afghanistan. The Rome initiative called for fair elections, support for [[Islam]] as the foundation of the Afghan state, and respect for human rights.\n**The second was based in [[Cyprus]] and led by [[Homayoun Jarir]], a member of the [[Hezb-e-Islami|Islamic Party]] of his father-in-law, [[Gulbuddin Hekmatyar]]. Critics of the Cyprus initiative suspected that it served the interests of [[Iran]]. The members of the Cyprus initiative, however, considered themselves closer to the Afghan people and regard the Rome group as too close to the long-isolated nobility.\n**The most significant was based in [[Germany]], which resulted in the [[Bonn Agreement (Afghanistan)]]. This agreement was made under [[United Nations]] auspices, established the Afghan Interim Authority and paved the way for the later jirgas that established the [[Constitution of Afghanistan]].\n**A lesser initiative based in Pakistan.\n* '''[[2002 loya jirga|June\u2013July  2002]]''' \u2013 Hamid Karzai elected to oversee it. This was possible only because in the fall of 2001, Karzai was able to successfully lead one of the largest southern Afghanistan tribes against the draconian rule of the Taliban. The Loya Jirga was organized by the interim administration of [[Hamid Karzai]], with about 1600 delegates, either selected through elections in various regions of the country or allocated to various political, cultural, and religious groups. It was held in a large tent in the grounds of Kabul Polytechnic from June 11 and was scheduled to last about a week. It formed a new [[Afghan Transitional Administration|Transitional Administration]] that took office shortly thereafter.\n*'''[[2003 Loya jirga|December 2003]]''' \u2013 To consider the [[Constitution of Afghanistan|proposed Afghan Constitution]].\n*'''2006''' \u2013 Afghan president Hamid Karzai said that he and the Pakistani president will jointly lead a loya jirga to end a dispute over border attacks.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.ipcs.org/Oct_06_pakistan.pdf |format=PDF |work=[[Frontier Post]] |date=October 1, 2006 |title=Musharraf, Karzai to lead Loya jirga |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927030558/http://www.ipcs.org/Oct_06_pakistan.pdf |archivedate=September 27, 2007}}</ref>\n*'''December 2009''', after his disputed [[Afghan presidential election, 2009|re-election]], President Hamid Karzai announced to move ahead with a plan for a loya jirga to discuss the [[Taliban insurgency]]. The Taliban was invited to take part in this Jirga,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rferl.org/content/Karzai_To_Unveil_Afghan_Cabinet_In_Days/1896326.html |title=Karzai To Unveil Afghan Cabinet In Days |publisher=Rferl.org |date=2009-12-06 |accessdate=2013-04-15}}</ref> but they declined.\n*'''[[Afghan Peace Jirga 2010|June 2010]]''', at Kabul, in which around 1,600<ref>[https://news.yahoo.com/s/afp/20100603/wl_sthasia_afp/afghanistanunrestpoliticsjirga_20100603164948 Afghan jirga seen as 'last hope' for peace] {{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> delegates of all ethnic groups attended for a peace talks with the Taliban.<ref>[https://news.yahoo.com/s/nm/20100604/ts_nm/us_afghanistan_jirga_21 Afghan jirga to call for peace with Taliban] {{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n*'''17 November 2013''', at Kabul, in which around 2,500 Afghan elders approved the presence of a limited number of US forces beyond 2014.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://edition.cnn.com/2013/11/24/world/asia/us-afghanistan-security-agreement/ |title=Loya jirga approves U.S.-Afghan security deal; asks Karzai to sign |publisher=CNN |date=17 November 2013 |accessdate=2016-12-27}}</ref>\n*'''April 29, 2019 \u2013 May 3, 2019''', at the [[Bagh-e Bala Palace]] in Kabul, held to agree a common approach to peace talks with the Taliban, amid [[negotiations between the Taliban and the United States]]. The jirga was chaired by [[Abdul Rasul Sayyaf]] and over 3,200 delegates attended. The Taliban refused to attend.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rferl.org/a/afghanistan-opens-loya-jirga-grand-assembly-to-discuss-peace-talks/29909992.html |title=Afghanistan Opens Loya Jirga To Discuss Peace Talks\n |publisher=RFE/RL |date=29 April 2019 |accessdate=2019-07-14}}</ref>\n\n==British India and Pakistan== Loya Jirga is not a joke officialy this is for Afghan cause.\n\nIn April 2006, former [[Balochistan (Pakistan)|Balochistan]] [[Chief Minister]] [[Taj Muhammad Jamali]] offered to arrange a meeting between [[List of Presidents of Pakistan|President]] [[Pervez Musharraf]] and a loya jirga for peace in [[Balochistan (Pakistan)|Balochistan]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailytimes.com.pk/default.asp?page=2006\\04\\29\\story_29-4-2006_pg7_16 |title=Leading News Resource of Pakistan |publisher=Daily Times |date=2006-04-29 |accessdate=2013-04-15}}</ref> A loya jirga was held at [[Kalat, Pakistan|Kalat]] in September 2006 to announce that a case would be filed in the [[International Court of Justice]] regarding the sovereignty and rights of the [[Baloch people]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.dawn.com/2006/09/22/top4.htm | title = Grand jirga in Kalat decides to move ICJ | date = September 22, 2006 | work = The Dawn Edition | accessdate = 2007-07-11 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url =  http://www.indiaenews.com/pdf/23289.pdf |format=PDF| title = Baloch chiefs to approach International Court of Justice | date = September 26, 2006 | work = India eNews | accessdate = 2007-07-11 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Jirga rejects mega projects|url=http://www.ipcs.org/pdf_file/news_archive/oct_06_pakistan.pdf|newspaper=The Nation|date=October 3, 2006}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Akbar|first=Malik Siraj|title=Baloch jirga to form supreme council to implement decisions|url=http://www.dailytimes.com.pk/default.asp?page=2006\\10\\04\\story_4-10-2006_pg7_19|newspaper=Daily Times|date=October 4, 2006}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Afghanistan}}\n* [[National Assembly (Afghanistan)]]\n* [[All India Pakhtoon Jirga-e-Hind]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|33em}}\n* ''This article contains material from the [[Library of Congress Country Studies]], which are [[United States federal government|United States government]] publications in the [[public domain]].'' ([http://lcweb2.loc.gov/frd/cs/aftoc.html])\n\n==External links==\n\n{{Afghanistan topics}}\n{{Pashtun nationalism}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Loya Jirga}}\n[[Category:Afghan culture]]\n[[Category:Pashtun culture]]\n[[Category:Government of Afghanistan]]\n[[Category:Politics of Khyber Pakhtunkhwa]]\n[[Category:Politics of the Federally Administered Tribal Areas]]\n[[Category:Politics of Balochistan, Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Pashtun politics]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Pashtun legal assembly convened for major national issues}}\n[[File:Hamid Karzai became winner at the 2002 Loya Jirga.jpg|thumb|300px|right|[[Hamid Karzai]] appointed as President of the [[List of Afghan Transitional Administration personnel|Afghan Transitional Administration]] at the [[2002 Loya Jirga|13 July 2002]] ''loya jirga'' held in [[Kabul]], [[Afghanistan]].]]\n\nA '''''loya jirga''''' ({{lang-ps|\u0644\u0648\u064a\u0647 \u062c\u0631\u06ab\u0647}}, \"grand assembly\") is a special type of ''[[jirga]]'', or legal assembly, in [[Pashtunwali]], the traditional code of laws of the [[Pashtun people]]. It is mainly organized for choosing a new [[head of state]] in case of sudden death, adopting a new constitution, or to settle national or regional issue such as war.<ref name=\"news.bbc.co.uk\">{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/1782079.stm | work=BBC News | title=Q&A: What is a loya jirga? | date=July 1, 2002 | accessdate=May 11, 2010}}</ref> It predates modern-day written or fixed laws and is mostly favored by the [[Pashtun people]] but to a lesser extent by other nearby groups that have been influenced by Pashtuns (historically known as [[Afghan (ethnonym)|Afghans]]).\n\nIn [[Afghanistan]], ''loya jirgas'' have been reportedly organized since at least the early 18th century when the [[Hotaki dynasty|Hotaki]] and [[Durrani dynasty|Durrani]] dynasties rose to power.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/09/11/opinion/11krakauer.html?scp=8&sq=jon%20krakauer&st=cse |title=To Save Afghanistan, Look to Its Past |author=Jon Krakauer |newspaper=New York Times |date=September 11, 2009 |accessdate=2014-10-29}}</ref>\n\n==History and terminology ==\n\nThere is a myth in the sense that the ancient [[Aryan]] tribes, who are hypothesized to have spoken [[Proto-Indo-Iranian language|Proto-Indo-Iranian]], came down in intermittent waves from [[Central Asia]] and Afghanistan. They practiced a sort of ''jirga'' system with two types of councils \u2013 ''{{transl|pus|simite}}'' and ''{{transl|pus|sabh\u0101}}''. The ''{{transl|pus|simite}}'' (summit) comprised elders and tribal chiefs. The king also joined sessions of the ''{{transl|pus|simite}}''. ''Sabh\u0101'' was a sort of rural council. In India it is referred to as ''Samiti'' and ''Sabha''.\n\nIt was used over time for the selection of rulers and headmen and the airing of matters of principle. From the time of the great Kushan ruler [[Kanishka]] to the 1970s, there were sixteen [[nation]]al ''loya jirgas'' and hundreds of smaller ones. The institution, which is centuries old, is a similar idea to the Islamic ''[[shura]]'' (consultative assembly).<ref name=\"news.bbc.co.uk\"/>\n\nIn the [[Demographics of Afghanistan|Afghan society]], the ''loya jirga'' is still maintained and favored, mostly by tribal leaders to solve internal or external disputes with other tribes. In some cases it functions like a [[town hall meeting]].\n\nWhen the Afghans took power they tried to legitimize their hold with such a ''jirga''. While in the beginning only Pashtuns were allowed to participate in the ''jirgas'', later other ethnic groups like [[Tajik people|Tajiks]] and [[Hazara people|Hazaras]] were allowed to participate as well, however they were little more than observers. The member of the ''jirgas'' were mostly members of the Royal Family, religious leaders and tribal leaders of the Afghans. King [[Amanullah Khan]] institutionalized the ''jirga''. From Amanullah until the reign of [[Mohammed Zahir Shah]] (1933\u20131973) and [[Mohammed Daoud Khan]] (1973\u20131978) the ''jirga'' was recognized as a common meeting of regional Pashtun leaders.\n\nThe meetings do not have scheduled occurrences, but rather are called for when issues or disputes arise. There is no time limit for a ''loya jirga'' to conclude, and the meetings often take time because decisions can only be made as a group and arguments can drag out for days. Various issues can be addressed such as major disaster, foreign policy, declaration of war, the legitimacy of leaders, and the introduction of new ideas and laws.\n\n==Afghanistan==\nSome of the historical ''loya jirgas'' in the [[history of Afghanistan]] are:\n*'''1707\u20131709''' \u2013 ''Loya jirga'' was gathered by [[Mir Wais Hotak]] at [[Kandahar]] in 1707, but according to [[Ghulam Mohammad Ghobar]] it was gathered in Manja in 1709.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://wolas.beepworld.de/mirwaisneeka.htm |title=Mirwais Neeka |publisher=Wolas.beepworld.de |date= |accessdate=2013-04-15}}</ref>\n*'''October 1747''' \u2013 A ''jirga'' at [[Kandahar]] was attended by Afghan representatives who appointed [[Ahmad Shah Durrani]] as their new leader.\n*'''September 1928''' \u2013 A ''jirga'' at [[Paghman]], called by [[King Amanullah]], the third loya jirga of his reign (1919\u20131929) to discuss reforms.\n*'''September 1930''' \u2013 A ''jirga'' of 286 called by [[Mohammed Nadir Shah]] to confirm his accession to the throne.\n*'''1941''' \u2013 Called by [[Mohammed Zahir Shah]] to approve neutrality in [[World War II]].\n*'''1947''' \u2013 Held by Pashtuns in the [[FATA|Tribal Agencies]] to choose between joining [[India]] or [[Pakistan]].\n*'''July 26, 1949''' \u2013 [[Afghanistan-Pakistan relations]] rapidly deteriorated over a dispute, officially declared that it did not recognize the 1893 [[Durand Line]] border any longer between the two countries.<ref>Agha Amin, [http://www.chowk.com/ilogs/65724/47736 \"Resolving the Afghan-Pakistan Border Question\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081012045458/http://www.chowk.com/ilogs/65724/47736 |date=October 12, 2008}}, ''Journal of Afghanistan Studies'', Kabul, (accessed December 12, 2009).</ref>\n*'''September 1964''' \u2013 A meeting of 452 called by [[Mohammed Zahir Shah]] to approve a new constitution.\n*'''July 1974''' \u2013 A meeting with Pakistan over the Durand Line.\n*'''[[1977 Afghan Constitutional Assembly election|January 1977]]''' \u2013 Approved the new constitution of [[Mohammed Daoud Khan]] establishing one-party rule in the [[Daouds Republic of Afghanistan|Republic of Afghanistan]].\n*'''April 1985''' \u2013 To ratify the new constitution of the [[Democratic Republic of Afghanistan]].\n*'''September 2001''' \u2013 Four different loya jirga movements anticipating the end of [[Taliban]] rule. Little communication took place between each of them.\n**The first was based in [[Rome]] around [[Mohammed Zahir Shah]], and it reflected the interests of moderate Pashtuns from Afghanistan. The Rome initiative called for fair elections, support for [[Islam]] as the foundation of the Afghan state, and respect for human rights.\n**The second was based in [[Cyprus]] and led by [[Homayoun Jarir]], a member of the [[Hezb-e-Islami|Islamic Party]] of his father-in-law, [[Gulbuddin Hekmatyar]]. Critics of the Cyprus initiative suspected that it served the interests of [[Iran]]. The members of the Cyprus initiative, however, considered themselves closer to the Afghan people and regard the Rome group as too close to the long-isolated nobility.\n**The most significant was based in [[Germany]], which resulted in the [[Bonn Agreement (Afghanistan)]]. This agreement was made under [[United Nations]] auspices, established the Afghan Interim Authority and paved the way for the later jirgas that established the [[Constitution of Afghanistan]].\n**A lesser initiative based in Pakistan.\n* '''[[2002 loya jirga|June\u2013July  2002]]''' \u2013 Hamid Karzai elected to oversee it. This was possible only because in the fall of 2001, Karzai was able to successfully lead one of the largest southern Afghanistan tribes against the draconian rule of the Taliban. The Loya Jirga was organized by the interim administration of [[Hamid Karzai]], with about 1600 delegates, either selected through elections in various regions of the country or allocated to various political, cultural, and religious groups. It was held in a large tent in the grounds of Kabul Polytechnic from June 11 and was scheduled to last about a week. It formed a new [[Afghan Transitional Administration|Transitional Administration]] that took office shortly thereafter.\n*'''[[2003 Loya jirga|December 2003]]''' \u2013 To consider the [[Constitution of Afghanistan|proposed Afghan Constitution]].\n*'''2006''' \u2013 Afghan president Hamid Karzai said that he and the Pakistani president will jointly lead a loya jirga to end a dispute over border attacks.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.ipcs.org/Oct_06_pakistan.pdf |format=PDF |work=[[Frontier Post]] |date=October 1, 2006 |title=Musharraf, Karzai to lead Loya jirga |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927030558/http://www.ipcs.org/Oct_06_pakistan.pdf |archivedate=September 27, 2007}}</ref>\n*'''December 2009''', after his disputed [[Afghan presidential election, 2009|re-election]], President Hamid Karzai announced to move ahead with a plan for a loya jirga to discuss the [[Taliban insurgency]]. The Taliban was invited to take part in this Jirga,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rferl.org/content/Karzai_To_Unveil_Afghan_Cabinet_In_Days/1896326.html |title=Karzai To Unveil Afghan Cabinet In Days |publisher=Rferl.org |date=2009-12-06 |accessdate=2013-04-15}}</ref> but they declined.\n*'''[[Afghan Peace Jirga 2010|June 2010]]''', at Kabul, in which around 1,600<ref>[https://news.yahoo.com/s/afp/20100603/wl_sthasia_afp/afghanistanunrestpoliticsjirga_20100603164948 Afghan jirga seen as 'last hope' for peace] {{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> delegates of all ethnic groups attended for a peace talks with the Taliban.<ref>[https://news.yahoo.com/s/nm/20100604/ts_nm/us_afghanistan_jirga_21 Afghan jirga to call for peace with Taliban] {{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n*'''17 November 2013''', at Kabul, in which around 2,500 Afghan elders approved the presence of a limited number of US forces beyond 2014.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://edition.cnn.com/2013/11/24/world/asia/us-afghanistan-security-agreement/ |title=Loya jirga approves U.S.-Afghan security deal; asks Karzai to sign |publisher=CNN |date=17 November 2013 |accessdate=2016-12-27}}</ref>\n*'''April 29, 2019 \u2013 May 3, 2019''', at the [[Bagh-e Bala Palace]] in Kabul, held to agree a common approach to peace talks with the Taliban, amid [[negotiations between the Taliban and the United States]]. The jirga was chaired by [[Abdul Rasul Sayyaf]] and over 3,200 delegates attended. The Taliban refused to attend.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rferl.org/a/afghanistan-opens-loya-jirga-grand-assembly-to-discuss-peace-talks/29909992.html |title=Afghanistan Opens Loya Jirga To Discuss Peace Talks\n |publisher=RFE/RL |date=29 April 2019 |accessdate=2019-07-14}}</ref>\n\n==British India and Pakistan==\nOn June 21, 1947, in [[Bannu]], a loya jirga was held consisting of [[Bacha Khan]], his brother [[List of Chief Ministers of Khyber Pakhtunkhwa|Chief Minister]] [[Dr Khan Sahib]], the [[Khudai Khidmatgars]], members of the Provincial Assembly, [[Mirzali Khan]] (Faqir of Ipi), and other tribal chiefs, just seven weeks before the [[Partition of India]]. The loya jirga declared the [[Bannu Resolution]],  which demanded that the Pashtuns be given a choice to have an independent state of [[Pashtunistan]] composing all Pashtun territories of British India, instead of being made to join either India or Pakistan. However, the [[British Raj]] refused to comply with the demand of this resolution, in response to which the Khudai Khidmatgars boycotted the referendum.<ref>{{cite book |last=Ali Shah |first=Sayyid Vaqar |date=1993 |title=Afghanistan and the Frontier |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=c05uAAAAMAAJ |location=[[University of Michigan]] |publisher=Emjay Books International |page=256 |isbn= |editor1-first=Fazal-ur-Rahim Khan |editor1-last=Marwat}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=H Johnson |first1=Thomas |author-link1=Thomas Howard Johnson |last2=Zellen |first2=Barry |date=2014 |title=Culture, Conflict, and Counterinsurgency |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=B9ZZAgAAQBAJ |publisher=[[Stanford University Press]] |page=154 |isbn= 9780804789219}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2006, former [[Balochistan (Pakistan)|Balochistan]] [[Chief Minister]] [[Taj Muhammad Jamali]] offered to arrange a meeting between [[List of Presidents of Pakistan|President]] [[Pervez Musharraf]] and a loya jirga for peace in [[Balochistan (Pakistan)|Balochistan]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailytimes.com.pk/default.asp?page=2006\\04\\29\\story_29-4-2006_pg7_16 |title=Leading News Resource of Pakistan |publisher=Daily Times |date=2006-04-29 |accessdate=2013-04-15}}</ref> A loya jirga was held at [[Kalat, Pakistan|Kalat]] in September 2006 to announce that a case would be filed in the [[International Court of Justice]] regarding the sovereignty and rights of the [[Baloch people]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.dawn.com/2006/09/22/top4.htm | title = Grand jirga in Kalat decides to move ICJ | date = September 22, 2006 | work = The Dawn Edition | accessdate = 2007-07-11 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url =  http://www.indiaenews.com/pdf/23289.pdf |format=PDF| title = Baloch chiefs to approach International Court of Justice | date = September 26, 2006 | work = India eNews | accessdate = 2007-07-11 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Jirga rejects mega projects|url=http://www.ipcs.org/pdf_file/news_archive/oct_06_pakistan.pdf|newspaper=The Nation|date=October 3, 2006}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Akbar|first=Malik Siraj|title=Baloch jirga to form supreme council to implement decisions|url=http://www.dailytimes.com.pk/default.asp?page=2006\\10\\04\\story_4-10-2006_pg7_19|newspaper=Daily Times|date=October 4, 2006}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Afghanistan}}\n* [[National Assembly (Afghanistan)]]\n* [[All India Pakhtoon Jirga-e-Hind]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|33em}}\n* ''This article contains material from the [[Library of Congress Country Studies]], which are [[United States federal government|United States government]] publications in the [[public domain]].'' ([http://lcweb2.loc.gov/frd/cs/aftoc.html])\n\n==External links==\n\n{{Afghanistan topics}}\n{{Pashtun nationalism}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Loya Jirga}}\n[[Category:Afghan culture]]\n[[Category:Pashtun culture]]\n[[Category:Government of Afghanistan]]\n[[Category:Politics of Khyber Pakhtunkhwa]]\n[[Category:Politics of the Federally Administered Tribal Areas]]\n[[Category:Politics of Balochistan, Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Pashtun politics]]\n", "name_user": "202.69.12.245", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Loya_jirga"}
{"title_page": "Anju Kurian", "text_new": "{{short description|Indian film actress}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=June 2018}}\n{{BLP sources|date=July 2017}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Anju Kurian\n| image              = [[https://m.timesofindia.com/thumb/msid-63111145,width-800,height-600,resizemode-4/63111145.jpg]]\n| caption            = Anju\n| birth_place        = <!--Must be attributed to a reliable published source with an established reputation for fact-checking. No blogs, no IMDb.-->\n| birth_date         = {{birth-date and age| 9 August 1993}}\n| nationality        = Indian\n| citizenship        = \n| occupation         = {{hlist|Actor|model}}\n| home_town          = [[Kottayam]], [[Kerala]]\n| parents            = Anu Kurian\n| website            = \n| residence          = <!--Must be attributed to a reliable published source with an established reputation for fact-checking. No blogs, no IMDb.-->\n}}\n\n'''Anju Kurian''' is an Indian film actress who appears mainly in [[Malayalam]] films.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://indianmovieplanet.com/actress-anju-kurian-profile-biography-filmography/|title=Actress Anju Kurian profile biography filmography|last=Johnson|first=Lijo |date=19 October 2016|work=Indianmovieplanet|accessdate=27 Mar 2017}}</ref> Best known for her roles in the 2016 [[Malayalam]] film ''[[Kavi Uddheshichathu]]'' and the 2018 film ''[[Njan Prakashan]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/malayalam/movies/news/Asif-Ali-to-romance-Anju-Kurian-in-his-next/articleshow/52173913.cms|title=Asif Ali to romance Anju Kurian in his next|last=Sidhardhan|first=Sanjith |date=24 January 2017|work=[[Times of India]]|accessdate=27 Mar 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nShe completed her bachelor's degree from Hindustan Institute of Technology and Science, Chennai.\n\n==Career==\nShe started her career in the Malayalam film industry with a supporting role in the movie ''[[Neram]]'' which was directed by [[Alphonse Puthren]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.filmibeat.com/malayalam/news/2016/anju-kurian-in-kavi-udheshichathu-225631.html|title=Pics! Anju Kurian To Debut As A Lead Actress Through Kavi Udheshichathu!|last=Abhijith|date=2016-05-09|website=www.filmibeat.com|language=en|access-date=2019-05-07}}</ref> The following year, she played a supporting cast [[Ohm Shanthi Oshaana]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/malayalam/movies/did-you-know/The-female-lead-of-Kavi-Udheshichathu-is-a-designer/articleshow/54827688.cms|title=The female lead of 'Kavi Udheshichathu' is a designer! - Times of India|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=2019-05-07}}</ref> She has also acted in several short films and musical videos.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.deccanchronicle.com/entertainment/music/110818/love-is-nature-and-nature-is-love.html|title=Love is nature and nature is love|last=das|first=sucharita|date=2018-08-11|website=Deccan Chronicle|language=en|access-date=2019-05-07}}</ref>\nIn 2019, she had two releases in Malayalam as female lead in movies [[Shibu]] and [[Jack Daniel]] respectively.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://malayalam.samayam.com/malayalam-cinema/movie-news/anju-kurian-and-karthik-ramakrishnan-starrer-movie-shibu-releasing-on-june-28/articleshow/69546304.cms|title=\u0d26\u0d3f\u0d32\u0d40\u0d2a\u0d4d \u0d06\u0d30\u0d3e\u0d27\u0d15\u0d7b\u0d4d\u0d31\u0d46 \u0d15\u0d25 \u0d2a\u0d31\u0d2f\u0d41\u0d28\u0d4d\u0d28 '\u0d37\u0d3f\u0d2c\u0d41' \u0d05\u0d1f\u0d41\u0d24\u0d4d\u0d24 \u0d2e\u0d3e\u0d38\u0d2e\u0d46\u0d24\u0d4d\u0d24\u0d41\u0d02|date=2019-05-28|website=Malayalam|language=ml|access-date=2020-01-22}}</ref>\n\n== Filmography ==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+\n!Year !! Title !! Role !! Director !! Language !! Notes\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|2013\n|rowspan=\"2\"|''[[Neram]]''\n|Mathew's sister\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[Alphonse Puthren]]\n|[[Malayalam]] \n|rowspan=\"2\"|Uncredited\n|-\n| Vetri's sister\n| 