{"title_page": "Yuki Bhambri", "text_new": "{{short description|Indian tennis player}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=January 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2011}}\n{{Infobox tennis biography\n| name=Yuki Bhambri\n| image=Bhambri RG18 (13) (29106556688).jpg\n| country={{IND}}\n| residence=[[Bradenton, Florida|Bradenton]], [[Florida]], USA\n| birth_date={{birth date and age|df=yes|1992|07|04}}\n| birth_place=[[New Delhi]], India\n| height={{height|m=1.83}}\n| turnedpro=2008\n| plays=Right-handed (two-handed backhand)\n| careerprizemoney={{US$|913,713|link=yes}}\n| fitnesscoach [[Abhimanyu Singh]] \n| singlesrecord={{tennis record|won=26|lost=29|details=in [[ATP World Tour]] and [[Grand Slam (tennis)|Grand Slam]] main draw matches, and in [[Davis Cup]]|small=yes}}\n| singlestitles=0<br><small>7 [[ATP Challenger Tour|Challenger]], 12 [[ITF Men's Circuit|Futures]]</small>\n| highestsinglesranking=No. 83 (16 April 2018)\n| currentsinglesranking=No. 137 (26 November 2018)<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.atpworldtour.com/en/players/yuki-bhambri/bf55/overview |title=ATP Profile |access-date=8 January 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180106160550/http://www.atpworldtour.com/en/players/yuki-bhambri/bf55/overview |archive-date=6 January 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n| AustralianOpenresult=1R ([[2015 Australian Open \u2013 Men's Singles|2015]], [[2016 Australian Open \u2013 Men's Singles|2016]], [[2018 Australian Open \u2013 Men's Singles|2018]])\n| FrenchOpenresult=1R ([[2018 French Open \u2013 Men's Singles|2018]])\n| Wimbledonresult=1R ([[2018 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Men's Singles|2018]])\n| USOpenresult=1R ([[2018 US Open \u2013 Men's Singles|2018]])\n| doublesrecord={{tennis record|won=6|lost=6|details=in [[ATP World Tour]] and [[Grand Slam (tennis)|Grand Slam]] main draw matches, and in [[Davis Cup]]|small=yes}}\n| doublestitles=0<br><small>6 [[ATP Challenger Tour|Challenger]], 1 [[ITF Men's Circuit|Futures]]</small>\n| highestdoublesranking=No. 138 (3 March 2014)\n| currentdoublesranking=No. 319 (26 November 2018)\n| AustralianOpenDoublesresult=3R ([[2014 Australian Open \u2013 Men's Doubles|2014]])\n| FrenchOpenDoublesresult=2R ([[2018 French Open \u2013 Men's Doubles|2018]])\n| WimbledonDoublesresult=\n| USOpenDoublesresult=\n| Team = yes\n| DavisCupresult = 1R ([[2010 Davis Cup|2010]])\n| updated=28 November 2018\n| medaltemplates=\n{{Medal|Country | {{IND}} }}\n{{Medal|Sport | Men's tennis }}\n{{Medal|Competition | [[Asian Games]] }}\n{{Medal|Bronze | [[2014 Asian Games|2014 Incheon]] | [[Tennis at the 2014 Asian Games \u2013 Men's singles|Singles]] }}\n{{Medal|Bronze | [[2014 Asian Games|2014 Incheon]] | [[Tennis at the 2014 Asian Games \u2013 Men's doubles|Doubles]] }}\n{{Medal|Competition | [[Youth Olympic Games]] }}\n{{Medal|Silver | [[2010 Summer Youth Olympics|2010 Singapore]] | [[Tennis at the 2010 Summer Youth Olympics|Singles]] }}\n{{Medal|Competition | [[Commonwealth Youth Games]] }}\n{{Medal|Silver | [[2008 Commonwealth Youth Games|2008 Pune]] | Doubles }}\n{{Medal|Bronze | [[2008 Commonwealth Youth Games|2008 Pune]] | Singles }}\n}}\n\n'''Yuki Bhambri''' ({{lang-hi|\u092f\u0942\u0915\u0940 \u092d\u093e\u0902\u092c\u0930\u0940}}, born 4 July 1992) is a professional [[tennis]] player from India. He is a former [[Junior tennis|junior]] no. 1<ref name=no1 /> and winner of the [[2009 Australian Open \u2013 Boys' Singles|2009 Australian Open Junior Championship]].<ref name=ao>{{cite web |url=http://www.itftennis.com/media/133602/133602.pdf |publisher=International Tennis Federation |accessdate=7 January 2014 |title=AUSTRALIAN OPEN JUNIOR CHAMPIONSHIPS |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150807043553/http://www.itftennis.com/media/133602/133602.pdf |archive-date=7 August 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref> He is the first Indian to win the junior Australian Open title and the fourth Indian in history to capture a junior singles title at a Grand Slam championship.<ref name=atpprofile /> He represents [[India Davis Cup team|India]] in the [[Davis Cup]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.daviscup.com/en/players/player/profile.aspx?playerid=100091581 |title=Davis cup profile \u2013 Yuki Bhambri |access-date=1 April 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160411121036/http://www.daviscup.com/en/players/player/profile.aspx?playerid=100091581 |archive-date=11 April 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Personal and early life==\nHe started playing tennis at the age of 6 years. His father is Chander and mother is Indu. He is the youngest in the family. His sisters are [[Ankita Bhambri]] and [[Sanaa Bhambri]], and he is the cousin of [[Prerna Bhambri]] and Prateek Bhambri, all of whom are professional tennis players. His early career tennis coach was Aditya Sachdeva.<ref name=atpprofile>{{cite web |url=http://www.atpworldtour.com/Tennis/Players/Bh/Y/Yuki-Bhambri.aspx |title=Yuki Bhambari \u2013 Profile at Association of Tennis Professionals |access-date=27 January 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150522024102/http://www.atpworldtour.com/Tennis/Players/Bh/Y/Yuki-Bhambri.aspx |archive-date=22 May 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.itftennis.com/procircuit/players/player/profile.aspx?playerid=100091581 |title=Yuki Bhambari \u2013 Profile at ITF tennis |access-date=18 August 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131109144539/http://www.itftennis.com/ProCircuit/players/player/profile.aspx?playerid=100091581 |archive-date=9 November 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> He is currently being coached by Stephen Koon, Impact Tennis Academy, and is accompanied by trainer Abhimanu Singh & Ahmad Nasir.<ref>{{cite news|title=Interview with Indian Tennis Daily|url=https://indiantennisdaily.com/2018/01/05/interview-with-yuki-bhambri/|accessdate=5 January 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180319004437/https://indiantennisdaily.com/2018/01/05/interview-with-yuki-bhambri/|archive-date=19 March 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Junior career==\nBhambri reached the junior No. 1 ranking in the world in February 2009.<ref name=no1>{{Cite web |url=http://www.itftennis.com/juniors/players/player/profile.aspx?playerid=100091581 |title=ITF Juniors Profile |access-date=3 January 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160321195200/http://www.itftennis.com/juniors/players/player/profile.aspx?playerid=100091581 |archive-date=21 March 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> He won the Junior Australian Open Boys singles title in 2009 by beating Alexandros-Ferdinandos Georgoudas of Greece in the finals.\n\nHe competed in all the junior Grand Slams in 2008. He lost at the [[2008 Australian Open \u2013 Boys' Singles|2008 Australian Open Boys' Singles]] in the semifinals to eventual champion [[Bernard Tomic]].\n\nYuki concluded his season by making history as the first Indian winner of the prestigious Orange Bowl at age 16, beating [[Jarmere Jenkins]] of the U.S. in straight sets.\n\nIn 2009, Bhambri began the year by winning the junior [[2009 Australian Open \u2013 Boys' Singles|Australian Open]], defeating Alexandros Georgoudas from Greece in the final in only 57 minutes. Throughout the tournament he dropped only one set, becoming the first Indian singles winner of the junior [[Australian Open]] and the fourth Indian in history to capture a junior singles grand slam title.<ref name=\"AO win\">{{cite web |url=http://www.australianopen.com/en_AU/news/match_reports/2009-01-31/200901311233382516296.html |title=Bhambri takes out boys' singles |last=Blake |first=Amy |date=31 January 2009 |accessdate=28 February 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101113143949/http://www.australianopen.com/en_AU/news/match_reports/2009-01-31/200901311233382516296.html |archive-date=13 November 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n{| class=wikitable style=text-align:center\n! Tournament !! 2007 !! 2008 !! 2009\n|-\n| colspan=10 align=left | '''[[List of Grand Slam boys' singles champions|Junior Grand Slam Tournaments]]\n|-\n| align=left | [[Australian Open]]\n| A\n| bgcolor=yellow | [[2008 Australian Open \u2013 Boys' Singles|SF]]\n| bgcolor=lime | [[2009 Australian Open \u2013 Boys' Singles|'''W''']]\n|-\n| align=left | [[French Open]]\n| A\n| bgcolor=afeeee | [[2008 French Open \u2013 Boys' Singles|1R]]\n| A\n|-\n| align=left | [[The Championships, Wimbledon|Wimbledon]]\n| A\n| bgcolor=afeeee | [[2008 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Boys' Singles|1R]]\n| A\n|-\n| align=left | [[US Open (tennis)|US Open]]\n| [[2007 US Open (tennis)#Boys' Singles|Q2]]\n| bgcolor=afeeee | [[2008 US Open \u2013 Boys' Singles|2R]]\n| bgcolor=ffebcd | [[2009 US Open \u2013 Boys' Singles|QF]]\n|}\n\n==Professional career==\n[[File:YukiBhambriDavisCup.jpg|thumb|250px|right|Yuki Bhambri in action during a Davis Cup tie]]\n\n===2009: First ITF title and Davis cup debut ===\nYuki obtained a wild card spot in the doubles main draw pairing with [[Harsh Mankad]] at the [[Chennai Open]]. At the same event he received a wild card spot in the singles qualifying draw in the [[Chennai Open]] where he lost to compatriot [[Sanam Singh]] in three sets. \nYuki also obtained a wild card position for the 2010 [[Australian Open]] qualifying draw as an additional reward for his win at the 2009 Junior Australian Open. \nAfter his win in the Orange Bowl, Yuki received a spot in the main draw of the [[Sony Ericsson Open]] where he lost to [[Diego Junqueira]] in the first round. Following his showing at the Sony Ericsson Open, Yuki played in an ITF Futures Event in New Delhi, India, where he won the tournament, becoming the youngest Indian to win a Futures event; Yuki continued this winning streak by capturing the title of the following Futures event held in the same venue. Yuki made his Davis Cup debut against South Africa in the World Group Play-offs.\n\n===2010: Youth Olympics Games Silver medal===\nIn August, Bhambri advanced to the finals of the first Youth Olympics Games in Singapore by defeating [[Damir D\u017eumhur]] in three sets. He played Colombian [[Juan Sebastian Gomez]] in the finals. After suffering cramps in his thigh, he conceded the match with the score at 1\u20134 in the third set. This gave him a silver medal at the [[Summer Youth Olympic Games|Youth Olympics]].\n\n===2012: First Challenger Title===\nIn May, Yuki won his first ATP men's doubles challenger title with compatriot [[Divij Sharan]] at the [[2012 Busan Open Challenger Tennis|Busan Challenger]]. They defeated the Taiwanese duo of [[Hsieh Cheng-peng]] and [[Lee Hsin-han]] in the finals.<ref>{{cite news|title=Yuki-Divij clinch ATP Challenger title in Busan|url=http://www.news18.com/news/india/yuki-divij-clinch-atp-challenger-title-in-busan-473884.html|accessdate=20 February 2018|date=13 May 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180220152405/http://www.news18.com/news/india/yuki-divij-clinch-atp-challenger-title-in-busan-473884.html|archive-date=20 February 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nA week later, he defeated [[Amir Weintraub]] in straight sets to win the first ATP Challenger singles title of his career in Fergana, Uzbekistan on 20 May 2012.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thehindu.com/sport/tennis/article3439214.ece |title=Yui Bhambri |accessdate=2012-05-20 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120521210858/http://www.thehindu.com/sport/tennis/article3439214.ece |archive-date=21 May 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===2013===\nHe reached his first ATP Challenger final of the season at [[2013 OEC Kaohsiung|Kaohsiung]], Taiwan. He lost to Chinese Taipei's [[Lu Yen-hsun]] in the final.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://sports.ndtv.com/tennis/news/214500-atp-challenger-brave-heart-yuki-bhambri-ends-runner-up-in-both-singles-and-doubles |title=ATP Challenger: Brave-heart Yuki Bhambri ends runner-up in both singles and doubles |publisher=NDTV |date=22 September 2013 |accessdate=4 April 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140610181326/http://sports.ndtv.com/tennis/news/214500-atp-challenger-brave-heart-yuki-bhambri-ends-runner-up-in-both-singles-and-doubles |archive-date=10 June 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nHe won his first ATP Challenger singles title of the season and the second of his career at [[2013 Traralgon Challenger|Traralgon]], Australia, defeating American [[Bradley Klahn]] in the final.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://ibnlive.in.com/news/yuki-bhambri-wins-traralgon-challenger-title/432189-5.html |title=Yuki Bhambri wins Traralgon Challenger title |publisher=IBN Live |date=27 October 2013 |accessdate=4 April 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140407114638/http://ibnlive.in.com/news/yuki-bhambri-wins-traralgon-challenger-title/432189-5.html |archive-date=7 April 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===2014===\nBhambri entered the [[2014 Australian Open]] in both singles and doubles. He lost to [[Potito Starace]] in the first round of the singles qualifying draw. He entered the men's doubles with [[Michael Venus (tennis)|Michael Venus]] from New Zealand as his partner. They defeated [[Roberto Bautista Agut]] and [[Daniel Gimeno-Traver]] in the first round. In the second round, the pair shocked tenth-seeded [[Jean-Julien Rojer]] and [[Horia Tecau]] by defeating them in straight sets.<ref name=rd2>{{cite news |url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2014-01-17/indian-challenge/46302031_1_yuki-bhambri-third-round-seeds |title=Bhambri-Venus stun No. 10 seeds Rojer-Tecau to make third round |publisher=The Times of India |date=17 January 2014 |accessdate=20 January 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140120005431/http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2014-01-17/indian-challenge/46302031_1_yuki-bhambri-third-round-seeds |archive-date=20 January 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref> They finally lost to the 5th-seeded Indo-Czech pair of [[Leander Paes]] and [[Radek Stepanek]] in round 3.<ref name=rd3>{{cite news |url=http://www.dnaindia.com/sport/report-leander-paes-ends-yuki-bhambhri-s-run-in-men-s-doubles-at-australian-open-1953604 |title=Leander Paes ends Yuki Bhambhri's run in men's doubles at Australian Open |publisher=DNA |date=19 January 2014 |accessdate=20 January 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140120233500/http://www.dnaindia.com/sport/report-leander-paes-ends-yuki-bhambhri-s-run-in-men-s-doubles-at-australian-open-1953604 |archive-date=20 January 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn 8 Feb 2014, Bhambri won his third ATP Challenger singles title at the [[2014 Shriram Capital P.L. Reddy Memorial Challenger|Sriram Capital PL Reddy Memorial ATP Challenger]] tennis tournament in Chennai. He defeated [[Alexander Kudryavtsev]] of Russia in three sets in the final. He also won the doubles title at the same event with his partner [[Michael Venus (tennis)|Michael Venus]] of New Zealand. The pair defeated the Indo-Slovak combination of [[Sriram Balaji]] and [[Blaz Rola]] in the doubles final.<ref name=CT4>{{cite news |url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2014-02-08/top-stories/47147846_1_yuki-bhambri-michael-venus-final-set |title=Double win for Yuki Bhambri at Chennai Challenger |date=8 February 2014 |accessdate=11 February 2014 |publisher=The Times of India}}</ref>\n\nLater in the year, Bhambri won two medals for India at the [[2014 Asian Games]]. He won bronze in the men's singles category, losing to Japan's [[Yoshihito Nishioka]] in the semifinals.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://sports.ndtv.com/asian-games-2014/news/230584-asian-games-yuki-bhambri-settles-for-bronze-in-men-s-singles-tennis |title=Yuki Bhambri Settles for Bronze in Men's Singles Tennis |date=28 September 2014 |accessdate=7 February 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141010103837/http://sports.ndtv.com/asian-games-2014/news/230584-asian-games-yuki-bhambri-settles-for-bronze-in-men-s-singles-tennis |archive-date=10 October 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref> He also won bronze in the men's doubles category with [[Divij Sharan]] as his partner. The pair lost in the semifinals to the Korean pair of [[Lim Yong-kyu]] and [[Chung Hyeon]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.india.com/asian-games-2014/yuki-bhambri-and-divij-sharan-settle-for-bronze-medal-in-mens-doubles-at-asian-games-2014-160171/ |title=Yuki Bhambri and Divij Sharan settle for bronze medal in men\u2019s doubles at Asian Games 2014 |date=28 September 2014 |accessdate=7 February 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924034312/http://www.india.com/asian-games-2014/yuki-bhambri-and-divij-sharan-settle-for-bronze-medal-in-mens-doubles-at-asian-games-2014-160171/ |archive-date=24 September 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===2015: Top 100===\nStarting the year as 315th-ranked player in the [[ATP rankings]], Bhambri qualified for the [[2015 Australian Open]], but lost to Great Britain's [[Andy Murray]] in the first round in straight sets.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.deccanherald.com/content/454333/yuki-battles-hard-losing-aus.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=19 January 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150119100035/http://www.deccanherald.com/content/454333/yuki-battles-hard-losing-aus.html |archive-date=19 January 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nHe then entered the [[2015 Delhi Open]] as a [[Wild card (sports)|Wildcard]] and reached the finals, losing to [[Somdev Devvarman]] in three sets 3\u20136, 6\u20134, 6\u20130. He maintained his good start of the season and reached the semifinals of the [[Kazan Kremlin Cup]]. On 13 September, he defeated [[Wu Di (tennis)|Wu Di]] in the finals of the [[Shanghai Challenger]] in three sets 3\u20136, 6\u20130, 7\u20136<sup>(7\u20133)</sup> to win his first title of the season, which helped him reach no. 125 in the ATP Rankings. He reached the finals at the [[OEC Kaohsiung]], losing to [[Hyeon Chung]] in straight sets 7\u20135, 6\u20134.\n\nHe broke into the top 100 for the first time in his career on 19 October 2015. He won his first title in India on 31 October, defeating [[Evgeny Donskoy]] in straight sets 6\u20132, 7\u20136<sup>(7\u20134)</sup> in Pune. As a result of his good run, he rose to a career-best ranking of 88 on 9 November. He finished the year ranked 93rd.\n\n===2016: Struggle with injury===\nBhambri entered the main draw of the [[2016 Australian Open|Australian Open]] for the second consecutive year. He lost in the first round to sixth-seeded [[Tomas Berdych]] in straight sets.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ausopen.com/en_AU/news/articles/2016-01-18/ao_analyst_bhambris_harsh_lesson.html|title=AO Analyst: Bhambri learns lesson|accessdate=27 July 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160820184617/http://www.ausopen.com/en_AU/news/articles/2016-01-18/ao_analyst_bhambris_harsh_lesson.html|archive-date=20 August 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn February he won his sixth doubles Challenger title at the [[2016 Delhi Open]], partnering with [[Mahesh Bhupathi]].\n\nBhambri was out of action from March to September because of an elbow injury.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Banerjee|first1=Sudeshna|title=After a year of struggle with injury, Yuki Bhambri looks ahead to 2017|url=https://www.sportskeeda.com/tennis/after-year-struggle-injury-yuki-bhambri-looks-ahead-2017|website=sportskeeda.com|accessdate=4 August 2017|date=8 December 2016}}</ref> This caused his ranking to drop out of the top 500.\n\n===2017===\n[[File:2017 Citi Open Tennis Yuki Bhambri (35509362094).jpg|thumb|250px|right|Bhambri in Action during 2017 Citi Open]]\nBhambri started his 2017 campaign at the [[2017 Aircel Chennai Open|Chennai Open]]. He won all of his qualifying matches and entered the main draw, where he defeated compatriot [[Ramkumar Ramanathan]] in the first round, before losing in round 2 to [[Benoit Paire]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Chaudhuri|first1=Sharmistha|title=Chennai Open: Yuki Bhambri crashes out after losing to Benoit Paire|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/tennis/chennai-open-yuki-bhambri-crashes-out-after-losing-to-benoit-paire/story-qP3qiu6rIgq3onNNTpWixJ.html|website=hindustantimes.com|publisher=hindustantimes|accessdate=4 August 2017|date=5 January 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170728113742/http://www.hindustantimes.com/tennis/chennai-open-yuki-bhambri-crashes-out-after-losing-to-benoit-paire/story-qP3qiu6rIgq3onNNTpWixJ.html|archive-date=28 July 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> \nHe then entered the qualifying draw of the [[2017 Australian Open|Australian Open]], where he lost in the final qualifying round to [[Ernesto Escobedo]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Australian Open 2017: Yuki Bhambri loses final qualifying round|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/sports/tennis/australian-open-2017-yuki-bhambri-loses-final-qualifying-round-4473697/|publisher=indianexpress|accessdate=4 August 2017|date=14 January 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170119232405/http://indianexpress.com/article/sports/tennis/australian-open-2017-yuki-bhambri-loses-final-qualifying-round-4473697/|archive-date=19 January 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn July, Bhambri reached the quarterfinals at the [[2017 Citi Open|Citi Open]] in [[Washington, D.C.]] This was his second quarterfinal on the ATP World Tour, and his first at a 500-level event. Bhambri defeated [[Stefan Kozlov]] in the first round and shocked 6th seed and defending champion [[Ga\u00ebl Monfils]] in the second round. He then defeated [[Guido Pella]] to reach the quarterfinals where he lost to eventual finalist [[Kevin Anderson (tennis)|Kevin Anderson]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Citi Open run helps Yuki Bhambri jump to 159 in latest ATP rankings|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/tennis/top-stories/citi-open-run-helps-yuki-bhambri-jump-to-159-in-latest-atp-rankings/articleshow/59958428.cms|accessdate=8 August 2017|date=7 August 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170812222340/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/tennis/top-stories/citi-open-run-helps-yuki-bhambri-jump-to-159-in-latest-atp-rankings/articleshow/59958428.cms|archive-date=12 August 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn October, Bhambri teamed up with [[Divij Sharan]] to enter the [[2017 Tashkent Challenger|Tashkent Challenger]]. They finished as runners-up, losing to the pair of [[Hans Podlipnik-Castillo]] and [[Andrei Vasilevski (tennis)|Andrei Vasilevski]] in the final.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bhambri, Sharan end runners-up at Tashkent ATP Challenger|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/tennis/top-stories/bhambri-sharan-end-runners-up-at-tashkent-atp-challenger/articleshow/61069758.cms|accessdate=13 November 2017|agency=PTI|publisher=Times Of India|date=13 October 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171116231827/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/tennis/top-stories/bhambri-sharan-end-runners-up-at-tashkent-atp-challenger/articleshow/61069758.cms|archive-date=16 November 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> In November, he won his second [[2017 KPIT MSLTA Challenger|Pune Challenger]] title, defeating compatriot [[Ramkumar Ramanathan]] in the final. This was his sixth Challenger singles title.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kumaraswamy|first1=K|title=Yuki downs Ramkumar to win Pune Challenger title|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/tennis/top-stories/yuki-downs-ramkumar-to-win-pune-challenger-title/articleshow/61704074.cms|accessdate=24 November 2017|date=18 November 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180205180116/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/tennis/top-stories/yuki-downs-ramkumar-to-win-pune-challenger-title/articleshow/61704074.cms|archive-date=5 February 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===2018: Return to top 100===\nYuki started the year with the [[Tata Open Maharashtra]] in Pune where he entered the main draw. He defeated compatriot [[Arjun Kadhe]] in the opening round but lost to Frenchman [[Pierre-Hugues Herbert]] in the second round.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Tamang|first1=Sylvester|title=Tata Open Maharashtra: Yuki Bhambri Loses To Pierre-Hugues Herbert In Round 2|url=https://sports.ndtv.com/tennis/tata-open-maharashtra-yuki-bhambri-loses-to-pierre-hugues-herbert-in-round-2-1795520|accessdate=15 January 2018|publisher=NDTV|date=3 January 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180116004334/https://sports.ndtv.com/tennis/tata-open-maharashtra-yuki-bhambri-loses-to-pierre-hugues-herbert-in-round-2-1795520|archive-date=16 January 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> He then entered the qualifying draw of the [[Australian Open]] and qualified for the main draw for the third time. He could not proceed further, losing to [[Marcos Baghdatis]] in straight sets 7\u20136<sup>(7\u20134)</sup>, 6\u20134, 6\u20133 in the first round.<ref>{{cite news|title=Marcos Baghdatis beats Yuki Bhambri|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/sports/tennis/yuki-bhambri-vs-marcos-baghdatis-live-australian-open-first-round-5025060/|accessdate=15 January 2018|agency=Express Web Desk|publisher=IndianExpress|date=15 January 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180116004236/http://indianexpress.com/article/sports/tennis/yuki-bhambri-vs-marcos-baghdatis-live-australian-open-first-round-5025060/|archive-date=16 January 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In February, Yuki entered the inaugural [[2018 Chennai Open Challenger|Chennai Challenger]]. He reached the final but lost to top seed [[Jordan Thompson (tennis)|Jordan Thompson]] in 3 sets.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Dasgupta|first1=Damayanti|title=Chennai Open: Bhambri goes down fighting to Thompson in final|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/tennis/top-stories/chennai-open-bhambri-goes-down-fighting-to-thompson-in-final/articleshow/62962189.cms|accessdate=19 February 2018|agency=TNN|publisher=TOI|date=17 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180811224752/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/tennis/top-stories/chennai-open-bhambri-goes-down-fighting-to-thompson-in-final/articleshow/62962189.cms|archive-date=11 August 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn March, he entered the [[2018 BNP Paribas Open \u2013 Men's Singles|Indian Wells Masters]] and qualified for the main draw. He defeated [[Nicolas Mahut]] in the opening round. In the second round he upset then-world no. 12 [[Lucas Pouille]] in straight sets. He eventually lost to [[Sam Querrey]] in the third round.<ref>{{cite news|last1=K|first1=Kumaraswamy|title=Treating Indian Wells Masters as any other tournament: Yuki Bhambri|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/tennis/top-stories/treating-indian-wells-masters-as-any-other-tournament-yuki-bhambri/articleshow/63272557.cms|accessdate=16 April 2018|date=13 March 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180313061734/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/tennis/top-stories/treating-indian-wells-masters-as-any-other-tournament-yuki-bhambri/articleshow/63272557.cms|archive-date=13 March 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Bhambri carried his good form to the next masters at the [[2018 Miami Open \u2013 Men's Singles|\nMiami Open]] where he qualified for main draw. There he defeated [[Mirza Basic]] in the first round before bowing out in the second round with a loss to [[Jack Sock]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Yuki Bhambri\u2019s Miami run halted by Jack Sock|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/sports/tennis/yuki-bhambris-miami-run-halted-by-jack-sock-5110898/|accessdate=16 April 2018|date=25 March 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180416134715/http://indianexpress.com/article/sports/tennis/yuki-bhambris-miami-run-halted-by-jack-sock-5110898/|archive-date=16 April 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn April, Bhambri won the first Challenger title of the season at the [[2018 Santaizi ATP Challenger|Santaizi Challenger]] by defeating compatriot [[Ramkumar Ramanathan]]. With this win he returned to the top 100 rankings.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Judge|first1=Shahid|title=Yuki Bhambri wins Taipei Challenger, set to return to top-100 ranking|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/sports/tennis/yuki-bhambri-wins-taipei-challenger-set-to-re-enter-atp-top-100-5138815/|accessdate=16 April 2018|date=16 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180416134857/http://indianexpress.com/article/sports/tennis/yuki-bhambri-wins-taipei-challenger-set-to-re-enter-atp-top-100-5138815/|archive-date=16 April 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn the back of his improved rankings, Yuki earned direct entry into the [[2018 French Open]]. This was his first match in the main draw at the event. He lost in the first round to [[Ruben Bemelmans]] in straight sets.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bhatt |first1=Gaurav |title=French Open 2018: Yuki Bhambri bites the clay on his Paris debut |url=http://indianexpress.com/article/sports/tennis/french-open-2018-yuki-bhambri-bites-the-clay-on-his-paris-debut-5196388/ |accessdate=13 June 2018 |date=30 May 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180613084754/http://indianexpress.com/article/sports/tennis/french-open-2018-yuki-bhambri-bites-the-clay-on-his-paris-debut-5196388/ |archive-date=13 June 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> He also entered the doubles draw with compatriot [[Divij Sharan]]. The pair advanced to the second round where they lost to second seeds and eventual finalists [[Oliver Marach]] and [[Mate Pavi\u0107]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hegde |first1=Prajwal |title=Day of defeats for India at French Open |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/tennis/french-open/day-of-defeats-for-india-at-french-open/articleshow/64419354.cms |accessdate=13 June 2018 |date=2 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180617171507/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/tennis/french-open/day-of-defeats-for-india-at-french-open/articleshow/64419354.cms |archive-date=17 June 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nYuki also got direct entry into the [[2018 Wimbledon Championships]] for the first time. He lost in the opening round to Italian qualifier [[Thomas Fabbiano]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hegde |first1=Prajwal |title=Yuki Bhambri crashes out of Wimbledon |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/tennis/wimbledon-2018/yuki-bhambri-crashes-out-of-wimbledon/articleshow/64832743.cms |accessdate=13 August 2018 |date=2 July 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181211062214/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/tennis/wimbledon-2018/yuki-bhambri-crashes-out-of-wimbledon/articleshow/64832743.cms |archive-date=11 December 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn August, Yuki opted to play at the [[2018 US Open (tennis)|2018 US Open]] instead of representing India at the Asian Games.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Saharoy |first1=Shilarze |title=Somdev stands by Bhambri's decision to play in US Open instead of Asian Games |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/asian-games/somdev-stands-by-bhambris-decision-to-play-in-us-open-instead-of-asian-games/articleshow/65437812.cms |accessdate=26 September 2019 |date=17 August 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191015224313/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/asian-games/somdev-stands-by-bhambris-decision-to-play-in-us-open-instead-of-asian-games/articleshow/65437812.cms |archive-date=15 October 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> With his participation at the US Open he completed playing in the main draw at all four grand slams. But he could not earn his maiden win at a slam event, losing in the opening round to [[Pierre-Hugues Herbert]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Patwardhan |first1=Deepti |title=US Open 2018: Yuki Bhambri's first-round exit ends his Slam season, but promises abound of better tidings |url=https://www.firstpost.com/sports/us-open-2018-yuki-bhambris-first-round-exit-ends-his-slam-season-but-promises-abound-of-better-tidings-5069011.html |accessdate=26 September 2019 |date=29 August 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190926084127/https://www.firstpost.com/sports/us-open-2018-yuki-bhambris-first-round-exit-ends-his-slam-season-but-promises-abound-of-better-tidings-5069011.html |archive-date=26 September 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nSoon after the US Open, Yuki started struggling with injuries. He played his last ATP event at the [[2018 European Open]]. Since then he has been out of action because of injuries, the correct diagnosis for which was made by [[Rafael Nadal]]'s doctor. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.olympicchannel.com/en/stories/news/detail/yuki-bhambri-injury-nadal-doctor/ |title=Rafael Nadal's doctor got my diagnosis right, reveals Yuki Bhambri |work=Olympic Channel |accessdate=9 February 2020|date=28 January 2020 }}</ref> He hopes to make a comeback at the French Open. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.olympicchannel.com/en/stories/features/detail/yuki-bhambri-tennis-injury-india-olympics/ |title=Yuki Bhambri and the wall: tennis star reveals mental struggle while injured |work=Olympic Channel |accessdate=9 February 2020|date=5 February 2020 }}</ref>\n\n==Tournament finals==\n\n===Singles: 12 (7\u20135)===\n{|\n|- valign=top\n|\n{| class=wikitable style=font-size:97%\n! Legend\n|- bgcolor=#e5d1cb\n| Grand Slam (0\u20130)\n|- bgcolor=ffffcc\n| ATP World Tour Finals (0\u20130)\n|- bgcolor=#dfe2e9\n| ATP Tour Masters 1000 (0\u20130)\n|- bgcolor=#d0f0c0\n| ATP Tour 500 series (0\u20130)\n|-\n| ATP Tour 250 series (0\u20130)\n|- bgcolor=\"moccasin\"\n| ATP Challenger Tour (7\u20135)\n|}\n|\n{| class=wikitable style=font-size:97%\n! Titles by Surface\n|-\n| Hard (6\u20134)\n|-\n| Clay (0\u20131)\n|-\n| Grass (0\u20130)\n|-\n| Carpet (1\u20130)\n|}\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Result\n! class=\"unsortable\"|W\u2013L\n! {{ns}}Date{{ns}}\n! Tournament\n! Tier\n! Surface\n! Opponent\n! class=\"unsortable\"|Score\n|- \n| bgcolor=98FB98 | Win\n| <small>1\u20130</small>\n| [[2012 Fergana Challenger|May 2012]]\n| bgcolor=moccasin|[[Fergana Challenger|Fergana]], Uzbekistan\n| bgcolor=moccasin|Challenger\n| Hard\n| {{flagicon|ISR}} [[Amir Weintraub]]\n| 6\u20133, 6\u20133\n|-\n| bgcolor=FFA07A | Loss\n| <small>1\u20131</small>\n| [[2013 OEC Kaohsiung|September 2013]]\n| bgcolor=moccasin|[[OEC Kaohsiung|Kaohsiung]], Taiwan\n| bgcol